                                        Archives
                                                                                                                                  Business Briefs

               
	 Mumbai, Jan. 7: Rating agency Standard amp; Poors today placed the corporate rating of Tata Motors under credit watch after it was named the preferred buyer for Jaguar and Land Rover. Tata Motors long term credit and foreign currency rating of speculative grade BB+ has been put under credit watch with negative implications, the agency said.
              
	 Calcutta, Jan. 7: A city court is likely to pass the much awaited order tomorrow on the criminal case against Rajendra S. Lodha filed by the Birlas in connection with their battle for the M.P. Birla group property worth Rs 5,000 crores.
              
	 Kuala Lumpur, Jan. 7: Malaysia and India expect to sign a free trade agreement (FTA) at the earliest, Malaysian foreign minister Syed Hamid Albar said today. 
              
	 Calcutta, Jan. 7: The Supreme Court has allowed Haldia Petrochemicals (HPL) to pay the fee of an auditor appointed by the Comptroller and Auditor General of India. The Bengal government considers HPL a deemed government company and hence the auditor was appointed by CAG, while The Chatterjee Group had been opposing the move as it did not share the governments view.
              
	 Islamabad, Jan. 7: Pakistan will sign a gas purchase agreement with Iran next week for a multi-billion-dollar pipeline project that also involves India. Pakistans petroleum and natural resources minister Ahsanullah Khan said India would be welcome to join the project when it is ready.
              
	 New Delhi, Jan. 7: Indians working abroad may be able to send money back home through mobile phones before the end of 2008, with the Western Union and Bharti Airtel planning to start the service by December.
              
	 New Delhi, Jan. 7: India Inc is the most optimistic in the world when it comes to business outlook, consultancy firm Grant Thorntons International Business Report said.
                                                            
